-- 
Glencore, HSBC, Rio Tinto, Tesco: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 
2011-10-09T23:01:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-09/glencore-hsbc-rio-tinto-tesco-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The FTSE 100 Index gained 12.14 points, or 0.2 percent, to
5,303.40. The FTSE All-Share Index gained 0.3 percent to
2,734.98, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index rose 0.5 percent to
2,562.74.  Aer Lingus (AERL)  Group Plc and International
Consolidated Airlines Group SA (IAG LN): IAG Chief Executive
Officer Willie Walsh said uncertainty around Aer Lingus’s
pensions will discourage anyone from investing in the Irish
carrier. Aer Lingus shares were unchanged at 0.65 euros, while
IAG stock fell 0.7 percent to 157.60 pence.  BG Group Plc (BG/)  : The U.K.’s third-largest natural gas
producer is studying the sale of some assets in  Brazil  to help
finance its $30 billion investment plan for the country through
2020, O Estado de S. Paulo reported, citing unidentified people
familiar with the matter. The stock gained 2.2 percent to
1,309.5 pence.  Diageo Plc (DGE)  : The world’s largest distiller’s Chief
Executive Officer  Paul Walsh  is seen as a leading candidate to
replace Unilever’s Chairman Michael Treschow, the Sunday Times
reported, citing unidentified people with knowledge of the
matter. The stock fell less than 0.1 percent to 1,272 pence.  Glencore International Plc (GLEN LN): The global
commodities trader may provide a debt facility for PT Bakrie &
Brothers Tbk to help it maintain a 47 percent stake in Bumi Plc,
the Sunday Telegraph reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares fell 2.4 percent to 422 pence.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  : South Korea’s KDB Financial
Group is interested in taking over HSBC Holdings Plc’s Seoul
branches, MoneyToday reported citing an unidentified official at
KDB.  Separately, HSBC denied that it sold assets in Brazil after
Sao Paulo-based Exame magazine reported the bank was in talks,
according to an e-mailed statement. The stock declined 0.2
percent to 509 pence.  J Sainsbury Plc (SBRY)  : The U.K.’s third-biggest
supermarket company will pledge to match the price of 13,000
goods with the price offered by rival supermarkets  Tesco Plc (TSCO)  and
Wal-Mart Stores Inc.’s Asda, the Sunday Times said, without
saying where it got its information. The stock fell 0.5 percent
to 292.2 pence.  Kalahari Minerals Plc (KAH)  : China Guangdong Nuclear
Power Group Co. is preparing a 650 million-pound bid for the
U.K.-based uranium miner, the Sunday Times reported, without
saying where it obtained the information. The shares surged 7.2
percent to 246 pence.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc (LLOY)  : Hugh Osmond’s Sun
Capital Partners Inc. is unlikely to enter second-round bids for
Lloyds’s branches, the Sunday Telegraph reported, citing
unidentified people with knowledge of the matter. The stock
slumped 3.4 percent to 34.66 pence.  Mouchel Group Plc (MCHL)  : The highway maintenance
services company is talking to banks about its debt after an
accounting error resulted in the erasure of 4.3 million pounds
($6.7 million) of profit from a contract and caused the stock to
plunge.  The company is receptive to takeover offers, the Financial
Times also reported, citing a person it didn’t identify. The
shares dropped 16 percent to 17.25 pence.  Rio Tinto  Group (RIO LN): The world’s second-biggest mining
company’s Murowa diamond mine agreed to cede a 51 percent stake
to the Zimbabwean government, the Harare-based Herald reported
today, citing Indigenization Minister  Saviour Kasukuwere . The
stock advanced 1.2 percent to 3,164 pence.  Sportingbet Plc (SBT)  : The company may sell its Turkish
business, a step that could spur Ladbrokes Plc to make a fresh
offer for the London-based bookmaker, the Sunday Times reported,
without saying where it got the information. The stock declined
0.5 percent to 45.75 pence.  Tesco Plc (TSCO LN): The U.K.’s largest supermarket chain
overhauled the management of a 4 billion-pound ($6.2 billion)
unit that includes its mobile and Internet businesses, the
London-based Times reported. The stock fell 0.2 percent to
405.35 pence.  Vodafone Group Plc (VOD)  : The world’s biggest wireless
carrier by revenue won’t bid for Lebara Group, a London-based
mobile virtual network operator whose owners are seeking 650
million pounds ($1.01 billion) for the company, the Observer
reported, citing an unidentified person. The shares dropped 1.2
percent to 169.75 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in London at 
 bgatt@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
